DateTime::::2016-01-24T15:12:03Z
While I agree with some of Emma Broke's opinions I don't believe she went far enough. It is okay for some things to die. Sesame Street has long been the best educational television show for children. Recently, someone saw the potential for profit and it was sold to HBO. I agree with the author's opinion that new money has ruined Sesame Street, but I think it is okay for some things to be just a memory. Watching them as reruns or YouTube videos wouldn't be a problem. It is actually better that they die than changing them for the worse, which would be making Sesame Street, for example, just about entertainment, and not education. Not everything needs to be sold to make money. Somethings are more important than money . . . like education.



Author::::chiefwiley
DateTime::::2016-01-23T18:19:50Z
The people producing shows for public broadcasting are often private entities operating for profit, whether it's This Old House or some other show. The local station carries The Lawrence Welk Show, which ran first in broadcast commercial television. Others started on UK television. Why does it matter what the first showing is on, or when, or where, or that the producer seeks to profit from it? The kids get to watch it for free on a broadcast public television network. Everybody wins.



Author::::RUwithmeDrWu
DateTime::::2016-01-23T01:39:52Z
My favorite thing about early Sesame Street was the way the short films and some of the animations had no obvious "point" that was being hammered home. Presented was simply an appreciation for the beauty of life, a combination of music and images that did not always feel the need to include some kind of testable "educational" content. Even a lot of the letter and number pieces were really about interesting combinations of sight and sound, including the astonishing counting cartoons with Grace Slick (if you didn't catch these to begin with, or haven't seen these on youtube --- you aren't doing anything more interesting right now I assure you!!) These cartoons have come to be tagged "Jazzy Spies", go, watch and listen. I crack up when I read commenters who say "I don't think these are really for kids." You're right, dumbass, kids should be dumbed down, you know, not exposed to cool stuff like this. 



