It is, at once, unbelievable and believable that Sesame Street has moved to a premium cable channel. Unbelievable because it is one of the few really innovative, child-centered pieces of TV production in the history of the US. Believable because the US is the home of the greed paradigm - it migrated there with the Puritans and scourged westward with the pioneers. The Brits are only in second place on the world greed index. This is just the capstone on the domination of American culture by those people controlling the wealth of the country. Everything is individual. The Austrian School is triumphant even without Ron Paul being elected President. There is no room in public discourse for the "common good" in the US. Everything will work out if only the rich can get richer. Hook, line and sinker Americans have bought the shaky, utterly-unprovable notion that money trickles down. The US is now the classic example of an upper class, hegemonic phenomenon undoing any notion of self-interest among working people. The theme song of Sesame Street will now only be licensed to be played in auditoriums charging $100 per seat or more. ASCAP will be vigilant to insure that it is not sung in American school classrooms without paying royalties because, after all, Sesame Street moved to HBO because it hadn't sufficient revenues on the public broadcasting system.



